V{{Infobox writer  <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].-->\u000a| name = Fatema Mernissi\u000a| honorific_prefix = \u000a| honorific_suffix = \u000a| image = 2004 Al Azm Mernissi Soroush Mernissi laudatio.tif\u000a| image_size = \u000a| alt = \u000a| caption = Fatema Mernissi ([[Erasmus Prize]] 2004)\u000a| native_name = {{lang-ar|\u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u0629 \u0645\u0631\u0646\u064a\u0633\u064a}}\u000a| native_name_lang = arabic\u000a| pseudonym = \u000a| birth_name = \u000a| birth_date =  1940  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\u000a| birth_place = Fez, Morocco\u000a| death_date = 30 November 2015  <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\u000a| death_place = \u000a| resting_place = \u000a| occupation = sociologist\u000a| language = \u000a| nationality = Morocco\u000a| ethnicity = \u000a| citizenship = \u000a| education = \u000a| alma_mater = University of Paris <br> Brandeis University\u000a| period = \u000a| genre =         <!-- or: | genres =      -->\u000a| subject =       <!-- or: | subjects =    -->\u000a| movement = feminist\u000a| notableworks =  <!-- or: | notablework = -->\u000a| spouse =        <!-- or: | spouses =     -->\u000a| partner =       <!-- or: | partners =    -->\u000a| children = \u000a| relatives = \u000a| awards = Prince of Asturias Awards\u000a| signature = \u000a| signature_alt = \u000a| years_active = \u000a| module = \u000a| website = \u000a| portaldisp =    <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit -->\u000a}}\u000a{{Moroccan literature}}\u000a'''Fatema''' (or '''Fatima''') '''Mernissi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u0629 \u0645\u0631\u0646\u064a\u0633\u064a}}; 1940 \u2013 30 November 2015) was a [[Morocco|Moroccan]] [[feminist]] writer and [[sociologist]].\u000a\u000a==Biography==\u000aFatema Mernissi was born in [[Fez, Morocco]]. She grew up in the harem of her affluent paternal grandmother along with various female kin and servants.<ref>[http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/dec/18/fatima-mernissi-obituary Fatima Mernissi obituary, The Guardian]</ref> She received her primary education in a school established by the nationalist movement, and secondary level education in an all-girls school funded by the [[French protectorate in Morocco|French protectorate]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Mernissi|first=Fatima|title=Beyond the veil: male-female dynamics in modern Muslim society|year=1987|publisher=Indiana University Press|pages=6}}</ref>  In 1957, she studied [[political science]] at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] and at [[Brandeis University]], gaining her doctorate there.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brandeis.edu/departments/sociology/grad/alumni.html |title=Featured Alumni |author=<!--Brandeis Department of Sociology; no by-line.-->|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>  She returned to work at the [[Mohammed V University]] and taught at the Faculté des Lettres between 1974 and 1981 on subjects such as methodology, family sociology and psychosociology. She became known internationally mainly as an [[Islamic feminist]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordislamicstudies.com/Public/fatima_mernissi.html |title=Mernissi, Fatima |author=<!--Oxford Islamic Studies; no by-line.-->|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\u000a\u000aMernissi was a lecturer at the [[Mohammed V University]] of [[Rabat]] and a research scholar at the University Institute for Scientific Research, in the same city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisemuslimwomen.org/muslimwomen/bio/fatema_mernissi/|title=Muslim Women: Past and Present|publisher=WISE|work=Fatema Mernissi|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> She died in [[Rabat]] on 30 November 2015.<ref name="nytobit">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/world/middleeast/fatema-mernissi-a-founder-of-islamic-feminism-dies-at-75.html|title=Fatema Mernissi, a Founder of Islamic Feminism, Dies at 75|date=9 December 2015|publisher=New York Times|last1=Fox|first1=Margalit}}</ref>\u000a\u000a== Scholarship and Recognition ==\u000aAs an Islamic feminist, Mernissi was largely concerned with Islam and [[Women in Muslim societies|women's roles in it]], analyzing the historical [[Islamic philosophy|development of Islamic thought]] and its [[Modern Islamic philosophy|modern manifestation]]. Through a detailed investigation of the nature of the [[succession to Muhammad]], she cast doubt on the validity of some of the ''[[hadith]]'' (sayings and traditions attributed to him), and therefore the subordination of women that she sees in Islam, but not necessarily in the [[Qur'an]].<ref>{{cite web\u000a|url=http://www.oxfordislamicstudies.com/Public/fatima_mernissi.html |title=Mernissi, Fatima |author=<!--Oxford Islamic Studies; no by-line.-->|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> She wrote extensively about life within harems, gender, and public and private spheres.<ref>{{cite web|title=WISE|url=http://www.wisemuslimwomen.org/muslimwomen/bio/fatema_mernissi/|work=Fatema Mernissi|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\u000a\u000aAs a sociologist, Mernissi mainly did field work in Morocco. On several occasions in the late 1970s and early 1980s, she conducted interviews in order to map prevailing attitudes to women and work. She did sociological research for [[UNESCO]] and [[ILO]] as well as for the Moroccan authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.morocco.com/blog/notable-feminist-fatema-mernissi/|title=Notable Feminist Fatema Mernissi |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>   In the same period, Mernissi contributed articles to periodicals and other publications on women in Morocco and women and Islam from a contemporary as well as from a historical perspective. Her work has been cited as an inspiration by other Muslim feminists, such as those who founded [[Musawah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musawah.org/honouring-fatima-mernissi|title=Honouring Fatima Mernissi|website=Musawah: Equality in the Muslim Family|access-date=2016-06-21}}</ref>\u000a\u000aIn 2003, Mernissi was awarded the [[Prince of Asturias Awards|Prince of Asturias Award]] along with [[Susan Sontag]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fpa.es/en/2003-fatema-mernissi-susan-sontag.html?texto=trayectoria|title=Notable Feminist Fatema Mernissi, Susan Sontag - Literature 2003 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> In 2004 she was awarded the [[Erasmus Prize]], alongside [[Sadiq Jalal al-Azm|Sadik Al-Asm]] and [[Abdolkarim Soroush]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.erasmusprijs.org/index.cfm?lang=en&page=Prijswinnaars&mode=detail&itemID=0ED2DDB5-BD03-7108-B3389BC6FD7B9B9C|title=Former Laureates|website=Praemium Erasmianum|access-date=2016-06-21}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Works==\u000aMernissi\u2019s first monograph, ''Beyond the Veil'', was published in 1975.<ref>{{cite web|last=Khaleeli|first=Homa|title=Fatema Mernissi|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/08/fatema-mernissi-100-women|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>  A revised edition was published in Britain in 1985 and in the US in 1987. ''Beyond the Veil'' has become a classic, especially in the fields of anthropology and sociology on women in the Arab World, the Mediterranean area or Muslim societies in general.\u000a\u000aHer most famous book, as an Islamic feminist, ''The Veil and the Male Elite: A Feminist Interpretation of Islam'', is a quasi-historical study of role of the [[Muhammad's marriages|wives of Muhammad]]. It was first published in French in 1987, and translated into English in 1991. The book was banned in Morocco, Iran, and the Gulf states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aquila-style.com/focus-points/mightymuslimah/fatima-mernissi-beyond-veil/80726/|title=Fatima Mernissi: going beyond the veil to fight misogynist interpretations of Islam|last=Evita Saraswati|first=Raquel|date=2014-10-16|website=Aquila Style|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-21}}</ref>\u000a\u000aFor ''Doing Daily Battle: Interviews with Moroccan Women'' (1991), she interviewed peasant women, women labourers, clairvoyants and maidservants. In 1994, Mernissi published a memoir, ''[[Dreams of Trespass: Tales of a Harem Girlhood]]'' (in the US, the book was originally titled ''The Harem Within: Tales of a Moroccan Girlhood'', and is still known by that title in the UK).<ref>{{cite book|last=Mernissi|first=Fatima|title=The harem within|year=1994|publisher=Bantam Books|location=Toronto|isbn=978-0553408140|edition=Bantam reprint.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Mernissi|first=Fatima|title=Dreams of trespass : tales of a harem girlhood|year=1995|publisher=Perseus Books|location=Cambridge, Mass.|isbn=978-0201489378|edition=26. printing. |others=Photographs by Ruth V. Ward}}</ref>\u000a\u000aShe contributed the piece "The merchant's daughter and the son of the sultan" to the anthology ''[[Sisterhood Is Global: The International Women's Movement Anthology]]'' (1984), edited by [[Robin Morgan]].<ref name="global">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.vsc.edu/lscfind/Record/154795/TOC#tabnav|title=Table of Contents: Sisterhood is global :|date=|publisher=Catalog.vsc.edu|accessdate=2015-10-15}}</ref><ref name="Moghadam2003">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hOVjBzQrdxkC&pg=PA76|title=Modernizing Women: Gender and Social Change in the Middle East|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|year=2003|isbn=978-1-58826-171-7|pages=76\u2013|author=Valentine M. Moghadam}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Bibliography==\u000a* 1975: ''Beyond the Veil: Male-Female Dynamics in a Muslim Society''. revised ed. 1985, 1987, reprinted London: Saqi Books. ISBN 0-86356-412-7\u000a* 1983: ''Le Maroc raconté par ses femmes''. \u000a* 1984: ''L\u2019amour dans les pays musulmans''\u000a* 1985: ''Femmes du Gharb'' \u000a* 1987: ''Le harem politique \u2013 Le Prophète et les femmes'' (trans. 1992: '' The Veil and the Male Elite: A Feminist Interpretation of Islam''. New York: Basic Books. ISBN 978-0201-63221-7)\u000a* 1988: ''Shahrazad n\u2019est pas marocaine''\u000a* 1990: ''Sultanes oubliées \u2013 Femmes chefs d\u2019Etat en Islam'' (trans. 1993: ''Forgotten Queens of Islam'')\u000a* 1992: ''La Peur-Modernité'' \u000a* 1993: ''Women\u2019s Rebellion and Islamic Memory''\u000a* 1994: ''The Harem Within'' (retitled. 1995: ''Dreams of Trespass \u2013 Tales of a Harem Girlhood'' New York: Perseus Books. ISBN 0-201-48937-6)\u000a* 1997: ''Les Aït-Débrouille''\u000a* 1998: ''Etes-vous vacciné contre le Harem?''\u000a* 2001: ''Scheherazade Goes West''. New York: Washington Square Press. ISBN 0-7434-1243-5\u000a* 2002: ''Islam and Democracy: Fear of the Modern World''. New York: Basic Books. ISBN 0-7382-0745-4\u000a* 2009: ''Les Femmes Du Maroc''. Brooklyn: PowerHouse Books. ISBN 1-57687-491-5\u000a\u000aEdited by Mernissi:\u000a* 1989: ''Doing Daily Battle: Interviews with Moroccan Women'' translated by Mary Jo Lakeland. New Brunswick: Rutgers University Press.\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a* [[Islamic feminism]]\u000a* [[Liberal movements within Islam]]\u000a* [[Asiya Andrabi]]\u000a* [[Mohamed Guessous]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{Reflist|2}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a* [http://www.mernissi.net/ Fatema Mernissi's website]\u000a* [http://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2015/11/173892/moroccos-sociologist-fatima-mernissi-dies-at-75/ Obituary on Morocco World News]\u000a* [http://www.mernissi.net/books/chronological_overview/index.html Chronological Overview of books by Fatema Mernissi]\u000a* [http://www.fpa.es/es/premios-principe-de-asturias/premiados/2003-fatema-mernissi-susan-sontag.html?especifica=0 Announcement of the Asturias Prize, 2003]\u000a* [http://elpais.com/diario/2008/07/06/eps/1215325610_850215.html Interview: El País (Spanish) 6-7-2008]\u000a* [http://elpais.com/diario/1989/10/31/sociedad/625791609_850215.html Interview: El Pais (Spanish) 31-10-1989]\u000a* [https://sites.google.com/site/mernissifatima/una-de-sus-obras-1 Interview: Encuentros Digitales El Mundo.es (Spanish)]\u000a* [http://elpais.com/tag/fatima_mernissi/a/ Articles in El Pais about Fatima Mernissi (Spanish)]\u000a* [http://en.qantara.de/content/portrait-re